The burial chamber is a {{ill|yokoana-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft}}, accessible from the south, with an overall length of 12.5 meters. The chamber's construction employs massive sandstone blocks. Artifacts recovered include earrings, jade, iron arrowheads, gilt-bronze harness fittings, and pottery ({{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|12=draft}} and {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft}}), indicating its construction in the late 6th to early 7th century. Adjacent to the southwest is No. 205 Kofun, believed to be a satellite mound due to overlapping pottery finds.
The kofun is considered the last key burial of a regional leader immediately following the cessation of {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumuli|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft}} construction in Saitobaru. Its similarities with the {{ill|Ishibutai Kofun|ja|石舞台古墳|12=draft}} in Nara Prefecture suggest close ties with the Yamato court.
