The burial chamber is a {{ill|yokoana-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yokoana-style stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}, accessible from the south, with an overall length of 12.5 meters. The chamber's construction employs massive sandstone blocks. Artifacts recovered include earrings, jade, iron arrowheads, gilt-bronze harness fittings, and pottery ({{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sue pottery|13=User:Immanuelle/Sue pottery|qq=}} and {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haji pottery|13=User:Immanuelle/Haji pottery|qq=}}), indicating its construction in the late 6th to early 7th century. Adjacent to the southwest is No. 205 Kofun, believed to be a satellite mound due to overlapping pottery finds.
The kofun is considered the last key burial of a regional leader immediately following the cessation of {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumuli|ja|前方後円墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/keyhole-shaped tumuli|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|qq=}} construction in Saitobaru. Its similarities with the {{ill|Ishibutai Kofun|ja|石舞台古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishibutai Kofun|qq=}} in Nara Prefecture suggest close ties with the Yamato court.
== Excavation History == * 1823 (Bunsei 6): Kodama Sanemitsu documented the chamber in "Hyuga no Kuni Kamiyo Ezu." <ref>{{Harvid|宮崎県史 資料編 考古2|1993}}</ref> * 1872-1888 (Meiji 5-21): William Gowland created schematic diagrams and introduced the kofun in his work on Japanese dolmens. * 1934 (Showa 9): Designated a [[National Historic Site of Japan]] as part of the "Saitobaru Kofun Cluster." * 1952 (Showa 27): Elevated to a [[Special Historic Site]]. * 1984 (Showa 59): Survey and chamber measurements. * 1995 (Heisei 7): Excavation and preservation work. * Reconstruction work restored the chamber's forecourt and part of its passage.
== Burial Chamber == The chamber measures: * Total length: 12.4 meters * Main chamber: Length 4.9 meters, width 1.75–2.45 meters, height 2.15 meters * Passage: Length 7.5 meters, width 1.8 meters, height 1.5 meters
Sandstone boulders form the chamber's structure, with a slightly rectangular shape that widens toward the entrance. Stones are layered in four tiers with slanted walls. The floor is paved with river stones. The chamber's roofing consists of three large slabs, while the passage also features river stone paving and three ceiling stones.
